00:00:09.488 --> 00:00:11.030 align:middle line:84%
>>BEN STEWART: Have
you ever wondered

00:00:11.030 --> 00:00:15.140 align:middle line:84%
if anyone or anything has ever
hijacked your decision making?

00:00:15.140 --> 00:00:17.660 align:middle line:84%
What if there are
creatures inside your body

00:00:17.660 --> 00:00:20.543 align:middle line:90%
that do exactly that?

00:00:20.543 --> 00:00:23.489 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:23.489 --> 00:00:29.890 align:middle line:90%


00:00:29.890 --> 00:00:31.730 align:middle line:90%
Welcome back to "Limitless."

00:00:31.730 --> 00:00:33.480 align:middle line:10%
In this episode, we're
going to be talking

00:00:33.480 --> 00:00:36.540 align:middle line:10%
about the holobiosis
and the gut brain,

00:00:36.540 --> 00:00:40.290 align:middle line:10%
but I'll start you off with
a quote from Hippocrates.

00:00:40.290 --> 00:00:45.120 align:middle line:84%
He says, "All disease
begins in the gut."

00:00:45.120 --> 00:00:49.030 align:middle line:84%
I was taught that we have one
brain, the one in our head.

00:00:49.030 --> 00:00:51.780 align:middle line:84%
And this brain was
responsible for every decision

00:00:51.780 --> 00:00:53.160 align:middle line:90%
I will ever make.

00:00:53.160 --> 00:00:56.710 align:middle line:10%
All things that I do
comes back to this brain.

00:00:56.710 --> 00:00:58.200 align:middle line:10%
So if I do something,
it's simply

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:01.470 align:middle line:10%
a calculated Ben-brain move.

00:01:01.470 --> 00:01:03.840 align:middle line:84%
But this was in the
'90s before the internet

00:01:03.840 --> 00:01:07.270 align:middle line:84%
made a lot of new research
readily available.

00:01:07.270 --> 00:01:09.660 align:middle line:84%
And what I came to find
is that we are anything

00:01:09.660 --> 00:01:13.420 align:middle line:90%
but one single unit of life.

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:17.430 align:middle line:84%
Therefore, we may not be
the only decision maker.

00:01:17.430 --> 00:01:20.760 align:middle line:10%
We may be actually closer to
what Rodney Dietert calls,

00:01:20.760 --> 00:01:24.660 align:middle line:10%
as the title of his book
suggests, "a Human Super

00:01:24.660 --> 00:01:26.550 align:middle line:10%
Organism."

00:01:26.550 --> 00:01:29.670 align:middle line:84%
Other researchers are
calling it a holobiont.

00:01:29.670 --> 00:01:34.170 align:middle line:84%
A holobiont is a unit of
life that is holistic.

00:01:34.170 --> 00:01:38.010 align:middle line:84%
So there's that word again
holobiosis, holobiont.

00:01:38.010 --> 00:01:39.900 align:middle line:90%
Holos means whole.

00:01:39.900 --> 00:01:44.070 align:middle line:84%
You see this in the word
holistic or holographic.

00:01:44.070 --> 00:01:47.050 align:middle line:84%
It represents the
entirety of the system.

00:01:47.050 --> 00:01:48.290 align:middle line:90%
So that's holos.

00:01:48.290 --> 00:01:50.640 align:middle line:90%
Biont is a unit of life.

00:01:50.640 --> 00:01:54.570 align:middle line:84%
But biosis is an
ecosystem of life,

00:01:54.570 --> 00:01:59.265 align:middle line:84%
many different organisms making
up one single super organism.

00:01:59.265 --> 00:02:01.840 align:middle line:90%


00:02:01.840 --> 00:02:05.100 align:middle line:84%
So how do microbes
truly fit the bill

00:02:05.100 --> 00:02:07.410 align:middle line:84%
when we're talking about
our human potential?

00:02:07.410 --> 00:02:09.990 align:middle line:84%
As we're talking about
who's the decision maker,

00:02:09.990 --> 00:02:13.590 align:middle line:84%
we really need to take a
deeper look at microbes.

00:02:13.590 --> 00:02:15.390 align:middle line:90%
What are they?

00:02:15.390 --> 00:02:19.630 align:middle line:84%
Why might we even
have them in our body?

00:02:19.630 --> 00:02:22.320 align:middle line:10%
Well, let's take a look at
a film called "Resistance--

00:02:22.320 --> 00:02:26.220 align:middle line:10%
Not All Germs Are
Created Equal."

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:29.220 align:middle line:10%
>> We have a very skewed
sense of our relationship with

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:32.285 align:middle line:10%
microorganisms in general
and bacteria specifically.

00:02:32.285 --> 00:02:35.470 align:middle line:90%


00:02:35.470 --> 00:02:39.325 align:middle line:10%
They collectively outweigh human
beings by 100 million times.

00:02:39.325 --> 00:02:42.070 align:middle line:10%


00:02:42.070 --> 00:02:45.960 align:middle line:10%
They can replicate 500,000
times faster than we can.

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:49.100 align:middle line:90%


00:02:49.100 --> 00:02:51.055 align:middle line:84%
And they've been doing
this for 1,000 times

00:02:51.055 --> 00:02:52.555 align:middle line:84%
longer than our
species has existed.

00:02:52.555 --> 00:02:56.040 align:middle line:90%


00:02:56.040 --> 00:02:58.120 align:middle line:90%
>>BEN: Very interesting.

00:02:58.120 --> 00:03:01.300 align:middle line:84%
These microbes, these
bacteria can rightly

00:03:01.300 --> 00:03:05.110 align:middle line:84%
be seen as ancient intelligent
organisms, actually

00:03:05.110 --> 00:03:08.950 align:middle line:84%
the most ancient intelligent
organisms on this planet.

00:03:08.950 --> 00:03:13.810 align:middle line:10%
So these microbes are so
crucial in every aspect of life

00:03:13.810 --> 00:03:16.970 align:middle line:10%
that they are here
to help us thrive.

00:03:16.970 --> 00:03:18.720 align:middle line:84%
They're in a lot of
the foods that we eat.

00:03:18.720 --> 00:03:19.870 align:middle line:90%
You go to the supermarket.

00:03:19.870 --> 00:03:24.310 align:middle line:84%
You see things like kombucha,
yogurt, kimchi, sauerkraut.

00:03:24.310 --> 00:03:26.860 align:middle line:90%
These are all fermented foods.

00:03:26.860 --> 00:03:29.800 align:middle line:84%
And in these fermented
foods live billions, if not

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:32.430 align:middle line:90%
trillions of microorganisms.

00:03:32.430 --> 00:03:35.680 align:middle line:84%
But in the 1900s, there
was this campaign,

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:38.830 align:middle line:84%
a scientific one at that,
saying that bacteria

00:03:38.830 --> 00:03:40.660 align:middle line:90%
are bad for your health.

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:43.840 align:middle line:84%
This gave rise to the
campaign of antibiotics,

00:03:43.840 --> 00:03:46.900 align:middle line:84%
depleting all the
bacteria in our body.

00:03:46.900 --> 00:03:50.140 align:middle line:84%
Scrubbing our hands and making
sure we're squeaky clean.

00:03:50.140 --> 00:03:52.870 align:middle line:84%
Mouthwash, making sure
there's no microbes in there

00:03:52.870 --> 00:03:58.100 align:middle line:84%
because it was the idea,
bacteria equals bad health.

00:03:58.100 --> 00:04:02.050 align:middle line:84%
But now that we actually know
more about these bacteria,

00:04:02.050 --> 00:04:05.320 align:middle line:84%
we know that there's good
bacteria and bad bacteria.

00:04:05.320 --> 00:04:08.240 align:middle line:90%
There's pathogens, bad bacteria.

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:11.050 align:middle line:84%
And there's probiotics,
good bacteria,

00:04:11.050 --> 00:04:13.510 align:middle line:90%
ones that help us digest.

00:04:13.510 --> 00:04:16.360 align:middle line:84%
The microbiome,
basically, the catch term

00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:19.540 align:middle line:84%
for all the microbes in
our gut, this microbiome

00:04:19.540 --> 00:04:24.460 align:middle line:84%
is responsible for roughly 80%
to 90% of our immune system,

00:04:24.460 --> 00:04:26.410 align:middle line:90%
keeping us healthy.

00:04:26.410 --> 00:04:28.390 align:middle line:84%
All these different
bacterial strains

00:04:28.390 --> 00:04:32.410 align:middle line:84%
communicate with one another
through a chemical language.

00:04:32.410 --> 00:04:34.630 align:middle line:84%
And with this chemical
language and a process

00:04:34.630 --> 00:04:37.000 align:middle line:84%
called quorum
sensing, they can tell

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:39.680 align:middle line:84%
what the populations
of these bacteria are.

00:04:39.680 --> 00:04:41.500 align:middle line:84%
If anything's getting
out of control,

00:04:41.500 --> 00:04:43.600 align:middle line:84%
they can bring it
back into balance.

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:46.060 align:middle line:84%
If there's a pathogen
or a parasite,

00:04:46.060 --> 00:04:48.070 align:middle line:90%
then they can get to action.

00:04:48.070 --> 00:04:52.760 align:middle line:84%
These microbes are responsible
for keeping us healthy.

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:56.260 align:middle line:84%
So how far back do these
fermented foods and this idea

00:04:56.260 --> 00:04:59.205 align:middle line:90%
of good bacteria truly go?

00:04:59.205 --> 00:05:00.580 align:middle line:84%
Well, you can look
back into time

00:05:00.580 --> 00:05:03.370 align:middle line:84%
into Western Africa
at the food garri.

00:05:03.370 --> 00:05:06.910 align:middle line:84%
It's a root vegetable
called cassava.

00:05:06.910 --> 00:05:09.610 align:middle line:84%
And this is a staple
there in Western Africa.

00:05:09.610 --> 00:05:12.340 align:middle line:84%
There's also the
Tanzanian togwa which

00:05:12.340 --> 00:05:14.470 align:middle line:84%
is a fermented
gruel, which actually

00:05:14.470 --> 00:05:18.100 align:middle line:84%
helps people in
malnourished countries

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:19.930 align:middle line:90%
maintain their health.

00:05:19.930 --> 00:05:24.640 align:middle line:84%
If you look in Asia, there's
soy beans, seafood, black beans,

00:05:24.640 --> 00:05:26.920 align:middle line:84%
fish sauce, and even
side dishes that

00:05:26.920 --> 00:05:29.800 align:middle line:84%
are all fermented and have
these good strains of bacteria

00:05:29.800 --> 00:05:31.090 align:middle line:90%
in them.

00:05:31.090 --> 00:05:35.080 align:middle line:84%
In Europe, you'll see
sourdough and sauerkraut.

00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:39.550 align:middle line:84%
Fermentation goes all the
way back to ancient Egypt

00:05:39.550 --> 00:05:42.380 align:middle line:90%
and likely beyond.

00:05:42.380 --> 00:05:45.470 align:middle line:84%
But what if I were to tell you
that these little critters,

00:05:45.470 --> 00:05:48.830 align:middle line:84%
these microbes in our
stomach, they not only

00:05:48.830 --> 00:05:50.300 align:middle line:90%
help our immune system.

00:05:50.300 --> 00:05:52.280 align:middle line:10%
They not only help
us digest food,

00:05:52.280 --> 00:05:55.170 align:middle line:10%
but they also
inform how we feel,

00:05:55.170 --> 00:05:58.990 align:middle line:10%
think, and make decisions.

00:05:58.990 --> 00:06:01.520 align:middle line:10%
So now let's take a look
at a film called, "The Gut,

00:06:01.520 --> 00:06:03.810 align:middle line:10%
Our Second Brain"
by CÃ©cile Denjean.

00:06:03.810 --> 00:06:06.520 align:middle line:10%


00:06:06.520 --> 00:06:08.920 align:middle line:10%
>> If Leonardo da Vinci
had had the chance to use

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:11.040 align:middle line:10%
the microscope
Michael Gershon uses,

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:13.165 align:middle line:10%
these are some of the
neurons he would've observed.

00:06:13.165 --> 00:06:16.970 align:middle line:90%


00:06:16.970 --> 00:06:21.850 align:middle line:10%
200 million of these neurons
line our intestine wall.

00:06:21.850 --> 00:06:24.340 align:middle line:10%
They spend the length
of our digestive tubes

00:06:24.340 --> 00:06:28.140 align:middle line:10%
helping us to digest food.

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:32.460 align:middle line:10%
Our two brains resemble
each other like brothers.

00:06:32.460 --> 00:06:35.070 align:middle line:84%
The upper brain houses the
central nervous system,

00:06:35.070 --> 00:06:38.202 align:middle line:84%
and the lower brain houses
the enteric nervous system.

00:06:38.202 --> 00:06:39.660 align:middle line:10%
>>MICHEL NEUNLIST:
The second brain

00:06:39.660 --> 00:06:42.240 align:middle line:10%
has had its name
usurped really because I

00:06:42.240 --> 00:06:45.390 align:middle line:10%
consider it to be the first
brain, the original brain even.

00:06:45.390 --> 00:06:47.520 align:middle line:10%
Primitive
multicellular organisms

00:06:47.520 --> 00:06:49.790 align:middle line:10%
were initially composed
of just a digestive tube.

00:06:49.790 --> 00:06:51.320 align:middle line:10%
[SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:53.340 align:middle line:10%
The enteric nervous
system developed

00:06:53.340 --> 00:06:54.690 align:middle line:10%
within this digestive tube.

00:06:54.690 --> 00:06:55.902 align:middle line:10%
[SPEAKING FRENCH]

00:06:55.902 --> 00:06:57.180 align:middle line:90%
[SWOOSH]

00:06:57.180 --> 00:06:58.740 align:middle line:90%
>>BEN: Very peculiar.

00:06:58.740 --> 00:07:04.200 align:middle line:84%
Before we even had neurons, or
a nervous system, or a brain,

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:07.830 align:middle line:84%
evolutionarily, the first
gut was the digestive tube.

00:07:07.830 --> 00:07:10.420 align:middle line:84%
That's how we learned about
our outside environment.

00:07:10.420 --> 00:07:12.480 align:middle line:90%
We would literally swallow it.

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:17.160 align:middle line:84%
Two brains, one in our
gut and one in our head.

00:07:17.160 --> 00:07:20.280 align:middle line:84%
They do communicate, and it's
a very important communication

00:07:20.280 --> 00:07:21.190 align:middle line:90%
process.

00:07:21.190 --> 00:07:23.250 align:middle line:90%
It's called the gut-brain axis.

00:07:23.250 --> 00:07:25.260 align:middle line:90%
There's five different channels.

00:07:25.260 --> 00:07:28.620 align:middle line:84%
A few of which are the vagus
nerve, the cranial nerve

00:07:28.620 --> 00:07:31.950 align:middle line:84%
that wanders outside of
the spinal column; the HPA

00:07:31.950 --> 00:07:35.340 align:middle line:84%
axis, which is the
hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal

00:07:35.340 --> 00:07:38.827 align:middle line:84%
axis; and simply through
chemical languages.

00:07:38.827 --> 00:07:40.410 align:middle line:84%
We have a lot of
microbes, and they're

00:07:40.410 --> 00:07:43.320 align:middle line:84%
communicating a lot of
very useful and valuable

00:07:43.320 --> 00:07:45.000 align:middle line:90%
information.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:49.050 align:middle line:84%
But there was this myth that we
have far more microbial cells

00:07:49.050 --> 00:07:53.340 align:middle line:84%
than we do human cells,
meaning far more microbial DNA

00:07:53.340 --> 00:07:56.580 align:middle line:90%
in our body than our human DNA.

00:07:56.580 --> 00:07:58.920 align:middle line:84%
They've brought that into
balance a little bit more

00:07:58.920 --> 00:08:01.170 align:middle line:84%
with this article that
says, "You're Probably

00:08:01.170 --> 00:08:03.100 align:middle line:90%
Not Mostly Microbes."

00:08:03.100 --> 00:08:06.240 align:middle line:84%
And, in this article,
they did new research,

00:08:06.240 --> 00:08:09.360 align:middle line:84%
and they came to find that
it's actually not true.

00:08:09.360 --> 00:08:14.070 align:middle line:84%
We are about half human
and half microbial.

00:08:14.070 --> 00:08:18.020 align:middle line:84%
Half the cells in our
body are not ours.

00:08:18.020 --> 00:08:20.950 align:middle line:84%
So could we rightly
say that these microbes

00:08:20.950 --> 00:08:23.530 align:middle line:90%
might be our puppet masters?

00:08:23.530 --> 00:08:27.130 align:middle line:84%
They cause us to crave
certain foods that feed them

00:08:27.130 --> 00:08:29.200 align:middle line:84%
and create their
optimal environment.

00:08:29.200 --> 00:08:34.169 align:middle line:84%
They cause us to behave, and
think, and emote differently.

00:08:34.169 --> 00:08:36.178 align:middle line:84%
This is a lot of
power that they have.

00:08:36.178 --> 00:08:37.970 align:middle line:84%
And this has been known
for quite some time

00:08:37.970 --> 00:08:40.940 align:middle line:84%
that a microbe can
change the behavior

00:08:40.940 --> 00:08:46.460 align:middle line:84%
of a macroscopic or higher-order
creature such as the killifish.

00:08:46.460 --> 00:08:50.310 align:middle line:84%
There's a very specific
parasite that gets into them.

00:08:50.310 --> 00:08:53.030 align:middle line:84%
And when it does, it
causes them to disobey

00:08:53.030 --> 00:08:54.610 align:middle line:90%
their primal command.

00:08:54.610 --> 00:08:57.830 align:middle line:84%
Their primal command is
swim very low in the water

00:08:57.830 --> 00:09:01.130 align:middle line:84%
so none of the predatory birds
can come down and eat you.

00:09:01.130 --> 00:09:02.580 align:middle line:90%
Makes sense.

00:09:02.580 --> 00:09:04.880 align:middle line:84%
But when infected
with this parasite,

00:09:04.880 --> 00:09:06.770 align:middle line:90%
they disobey this command.

00:09:06.770 --> 00:09:10.460 align:middle line:84%
They swim in the shallow
water, right towards the top.

00:09:10.460 --> 00:09:13.400 align:middle line:84%
Not only that, they
swim very erratically.

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:14.450 align:middle line:90%
They move a lot.

00:09:14.450 --> 00:09:17.210 align:middle line:84%
So the sun catches their
scales, and they could

00:09:17.210 --> 00:09:19.160 align:middle line:90%
be easier seen by the bird.

00:09:19.160 --> 00:09:21.770 align:middle line:84%
So the birds come
down, swoop them up.

00:09:21.770 --> 00:09:23.990 align:middle line:84%
Now the parasite
is inside the bird.

00:09:23.990 --> 00:09:28.220 align:middle line:10%
The birds drop all of their
waste onto this field.

00:09:28.220 --> 00:09:30.230 align:middle line:84%
The cows come by,
eat the grass that

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:32.000 align:middle line:90%
is infected with this parasite.

00:09:32.000 --> 00:09:34.190 align:middle line:84%
Now, the parasite
gets to live out

00:09:34.190 --> 00:09:36.920 align:middle line:84%
the rest of its illustrious
life in one of those four

00:09:36.920 --> 00:09:39.260 align:middle line:90%
stomachs of that cow.

00:09:39.260 --> 00:09:40.670 align:middle line:90%
That is smart.

00:09:40.670 --> 00:09:43.040 align:middle line:84%
In computer terms,
that fish just

00:09:43.040 --> 00:09:46.680 align:middle line:90%
got hacked by that parasite.

00:09:46.680 --> 00:09:50.400 align:middle line:84%
And they do this through
chemical languages.

00:09:50.400 --> 00:09:53.160 align:middle line:84%
They change the ratio of
these neural chemicals

00:09:53.160 --> 00:09:56.880 align:middle line:84%
and the chemistry in our body
to get us to think differently.

00:09:56.880 --> 00:09:59.160 align:middle line:84%
Literally, they are
hijacking our thinking.

00:09:59.160 --> 00:10:01.670 align:middle line:90%


00:10:01.670 --> 00:10:03.890 align:middle line:84%
Let's take a deeper look
at how many of these

00:10:03.890 --> 00:10:06.140 align:middle line:84%
bacterial strains
live in our body.

00:10:06.140 --> 00:10:09.710 align:middle line:84%
We have many different areas
in which these bacteria live

00:10:09.710 --> 00:10:11.450 align:middle line:90%
and many different strains.

00:10:11.450 --> 00:10:13.550 align:middle line:84%
For instance, there's
a different strain

00:10:13.550 --> 00:10:17.240 align:middle line:84%
of bacteria E. coli on
the bottom of your foot

00:10:17.240 --> 00:10:22.070 align:middle line:84%
than on the top of your foot, or
in your forearms, your armpits,

00:10:22.070 --> 00:10:27.080 align:middle line:84%
hair follicles, eyes,
mouth, digestive tract,

00:10:27.080 --> 00:10:29.630 align:middle line:84%
and even through
your bloodstream.

00:10:29.630 --> 00:10:32.600 align:middle line:84%
The unique thing about it
is every single one of us

00:10:32.600 --> 00:10:36.650 align:middle line:84%
has a very peculiar
ratio of these strains.

00:10:36.650 --> 00:10:38.600 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes we're missing
a strain or two.

00:10:38.600 --> 00:10:41.390 align:middle line:84%
Sometimes we have a few
that we shouldn't have.

00:10:41.390 --> 00:10:45.530 align:middle line:84%
But we all have our own unique
ratio, which is as unique to us

00:10:45.530 --> 00:10:48.350 align:middle line:90%
as our fingerprint is.

00:10:48.350 --> 00:10:50.380 align:middle line:90%
There's also an enterotype.

00:10:50.380 --> 00:10:54.550 align:middle line:84%
